{"title_page": "Diane Schenandoah", "text_new": "{{short description|American artist}}\n{{Refimprove BLP|date=March 2020}}\n\n'''Diane Schenandoah''' is a Native American artist known for her distinct sculptures and influence on the Oneida community'''.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://rematriation.com/diane-schenandoah/|title=Diane Schenandoah|last=|first=|date=|website=Rematriation Magazine|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>''' She occasionally serves as a backup singer for her sister, a First Native Grammy winner, [[Joanne Shenandoah|Joanne Schenandoah]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.amerinda.org/newsletter/5-3/diane.html|title=Diane Schenandoah|website=www.amerinda.org|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nSchenandoah was born in upstate [[Oneida, New York]] on October 21, 1958 to Clifford Schenandoah, an [[Onondaga people|Onondaga]] Nation chief and jazz musician and singer, and Maisie Schenandoah, an Oneida Wolf Clan Mother, as well as an artist and painter.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Goeman|first=Mishuana|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=kz_CCwAAQBAJ&oi=fnd&pg=PT6&dq=diane+schenandoah&ots=4N2mlsd519&sig=ygyL4g11ejIsmlxl6yz_zGCHd4c#v=onepage&q=diane%20schenandoah&f=false|title=Mark My Words: Native Women Mapping Our Nations|date=2013-04-12|publisher=U of Minnesota Press|isbn=978-1-4529-3936-0|language=en}}</ref>'''<ref name=\":0\" />''' She spent most of her early years in the Oneida Territory with her three sisters, Vicky, Joanne, and Danielle, all of whom were raised in their mother's  Wolf Clan. Prior to her parents' deaths they both encouraged their children to embrace their talents. Maisie collected ancient [[Iroquois|Haudenosaunee]] artifacts, which she gave to her children in order to help them be more creative. Through these artifacts Schenandoah learned how to create rattles, baskets, and other crafts from her culture.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nShe attended Syracuse University, where she received a Bachelor of Fine Arts, and then moved to New Mexico in 1979 to attend the Southwestern Indian Polytechnic Institute (SIPI). The following year she attended the Institute of American Indian Arts (IAIA) in Santa Fe, where she received her degree in Fine Arts/3D and Creative Writing.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zvMXZrRyUvIC&pg=PA35&lpg=PA35&dq=Spawning+the+Medicine+River:+Issue+9&source=bl&ots=SZk2_0ZlpL&sig=ACfU3U3HWxPg_fujBD883nv385yKI7hvAA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjv79nMiqXoAhXXFzQIHeFUDXYQ6AEwAnoECAsQAQ#v=onepage&q=diane%20schenandoah&f=false|title=Spawning the Medicine River, Issue 9|last=|publisher=Institute of American Indian Arts Press|date=|via=Google Books|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Art career ==\nSchenandoah became known for her ability to shape clay and carve stone, which she used to create sculptures that would help represent her culture. She additionally worked with wood and antler and casted in 18k gold, sterling silver, and bronze. A few years into her art career, she was taken on as a mentee by sculptor [[Allan Houser]], a famous American sculptor and painter. He even credited her artistry, stating, \u201cI have never had a woman apprentice but if I were to have one, you would be it.\u201d<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.amerinda.org/naar/schenandoahd/carver/carver.htm|title=NAAR {{!}} NATIVE AMERICAN ARTIST ROSTER|website=www.amerinda.org|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref> Schenandoah later stated that these words gave her the confidence and motivation to continue sculpting.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.artslant.com/la/artists/show/330692-diane-schenandoah|title=Diane Schenandoah|website=ArtSlant|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n\nShe has stated that she prefers to use as many natural materials as possible in her sculptures since she believes it was a blessing given to the humans by the hand of the Creator. Schenandoah has stated that she takes inspiration from multiple sources, such as using her own motherhood to inspire a series of sculptures featuring mothers holding their babies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amerinda.org/newsletter/5-3/giveitback.jpg|title=Diane Schenandoah|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to her sculptures, Schenandoah has a line of jewelry in honor of women being life givers.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/diane-schenandoah-b514285/|title=Schenandoah's Originals|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nSchenandoah has received multiple awards, which includes the [https://www.firstpeoplesfund.org/community-spirit-awards Community Spirit Award] from the [https://www.firstpeoplesfund.org/ First People\u2019s Fund]. She received this for her devotion to serving her community at Oneida, where she teaches creative writing, sculpting, and culture presentations. Schenandoah teaches in both public and private schools and offers private art lessons in clay and sculpture.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Select artworks ==\n\n* \u201cCalling All of Creation\u201d - Created using Ohio clay mounted on a black walnut base. The \"turtle rattles\" in the artwork were made from buffalo horn and the gustoays (hat) feathers that the two [[Iroquois|Haudenosaunee]] men are wearing were carved from wampum cohog shells and wild turkey feathers. This sculpture displays two Haudenosaunee men sitting down and facing each other on a bench as they shake their turtle rattles to a sacred form song.<ref name=\":1\" />\n* \u201cShhh\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpeoplesfund.org/diane-schenandoah|title=Diane Schenandoah|website=First Peoples Fund|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> - Created using clay. This sculpture depicts a mother intimately rocking and comforting her baby to sleep.<ref name=\":1\" />\n* \u201cBreath of Life\u201d<ref name=\":1\" /> - Created from original deer bone. This miniature piece can either be worn as a stickpin or part of a necklace. This sculpture honors women as life givers, which was a common theme for many of Schenandoah's artworks.<ref name=\":1\" />\n*\"The Journey Home\" (2005) - Created using buffalo leg bone, caribou antler, and butternut wood. This sculpture was formed to honor her ancestors and the path they journeyed, leading them back to the spirit world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/29261037@N02/21016993291|title=The Journey Home|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*\"Dancing with the Light\" (2014) - Created using maple, white ash, mixed clay, and geese feathers. 14\" x 3\" x 13\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paddle8.com/work/diane-schenandoah/60215-dancing-with-the-light/|title=Diane Schenandoah - Dancing with the Light, 2014|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*\u201cBeholding Beauty\u201d<ref name=\":2\" /> (2010) - Created using clay. 18\" x 24\".<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Select exhibitions ==\n\n*[[Heard Museum|Heard Museum Opening, Phoenix, AZ]]\n\n*[[Pow wow|Pow wow, Cruise, Bahamas]]\n*[[Everson Museum of Art|Traveling Exhibition, Everson Museum of Art, Barnes and Noble, Syracuse, NY]]\n*[[Munson-Williams-Proctor Arts Institute|Munson Williams Proctor School of Art, Utica, NY Schweinfurth Memorial Art Center, Auburn, NY]]\n*[[Six Nations|Six Nations - Six Artists, San Francisco, CA]]\n*[[Castellani Art Museum|Shadow of the Eagle, Castellani Art Museum, Niagara, NY]]\n*[[New York State Museum]] - Iroquois Artists, Albany, NY\n*[[Landmark Theatres|Silent Art Auction, Landmark Theater, Syracuse, NY]]\n*[[Sainte Marie among the Iroquois|Iroquois Artists of Today, St. Marie Among the Iroquois Museum, Liverpool, NY]]\n*[[Iroquois Indian Museum|Iroquois Museum Schoharie, NY]]\n*[[United World Colleges|United World College, Encounter New Mexico Juried Exhibit, Las Vegas, NM]]\n*[[Syracuse University|Bird Library, Syracuse University, Iroquois Art, Syracuse, NY]]\n*[[Berkshire Museum|Berkshire Museum, Women spirit; Focus on Women Regional, Pittsfield, MA]]\n*[[Navy Pier|Chicago's Navy Pier, Native Arts Conference]]\n*[[New York State Museum|New York State Museum, Thanksgiving Show, Iroquois Artist Today, 1983, Albany, NY]]\n*[[Institute of American Indian Arts|I.A.I.A., Graduates Show 1982]]\n\n* [[Fenimore Art Museum|Fennimore Museum, gift shop, Cooperstown, NY]]\n\n*[[Iroquois Indian Museum|Iroquois Indian Museum, Howe's Cave, NY]]\n\n* [[Seneca Niagara Casino & Hotel|The Seneca/Niagara Casino, Niagara Falls, NY]]\n* [[Mashantucket Pequot Museum and Research Center|Mashantucket/Pequot Museum, Ledyard, CT]]\n\n== Collections ==\n\n* Rancocus Nation Museum, Rancocus, NJ\n\n* New York State Museum, Albany, NY\n\n* \u201cThaw Collection\u201d Fennimore Museum, Cooperstown, NY\n\n* Mashentucket/Pequot Museum, Ledyard Ct\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n<br />\n[[Category:Oneida people]]\n[[Category:Native American artists]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Native American sculptors]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American artist}}\n{{Refimprove BLP|date=March 2020}}\n\n'''Diane Schenandoah''' is a Native American artist known for her distinct sculptures and influence on the Oneida community'''.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://rematriation.com/diane-schenandoah/|title=Diane Schenandoah|last=|first=|date=|website=Rematriation Magazine|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>''' She occasionally serves as a backup singer for her sister, a First Native Grammy winner, [[Joanne Shenandoah|Joanne Schenandoah]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.amerinda.org/newsletter/5-3/diane.html|title=Diane Schenandoah|website=www.amerinda.org|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nSchenandoah was born in upstate [[Oneida, New York]] on October 21, 1958 to Clifford Schenandoah, an [[Onondaga people|Onondaga]] Nation chief and jazz musician and singer, and Maisie Schenandoah, an Oneida Wolf Clan Mother, as well as an artist and painter.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Goeman|first=Mishuana|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=kz_CCwAAQBAJ&oi=fnd&pg=PT6&dq=diane+schenandoah&ots=4N2mlsd519&sig=ygyL4g11ejIsmlxl6yz_zGCHd4c#v=onepage&q=diane%20schenandoah&f=false|title=Mark My Words: Native Women Mapping Our Nations|date=2013-04-12|publisher=U of Minnesota Press|isbn=978-1-4529-3936-0|language=en}}</ref>'''<ref name=\":0\" />''' She spent most of her early years in the Oneida Territory with her three sisters, Vicky, Joanne, and Danielle, all of whom were raised in their mother's  Wolf Clan. Prior to her parents' deaths they both encouraged their children to embrace their talents. Maisie collected ancient [[Iroquois|Haudenosaunee]] artifacts, which she gave to her children in order to help them be more creative. Through these artifacts Schenandoah learned how to create rattles, baskets, and other crafts from her culture.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nShe attended Syracuse University, where she received a Bachelor of Fine Arts, and then moved to  to New Mexico in 1979 to attend the Southwestern Indian Polytechnic Institute (SIPI). The following year she attended the Institute of American Indian Arts (IAIA) in Santa Fe, where she received her degree in Fine Arts/3D and Creative Writing.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zvMXZrRyUvIC&pg=PA35&lpg=PA35&dq=Spawning+the+Medicine+River:+Issue+9&source=bl&ots=SZk2_0ZlpL&sig=ACfU3U3HWxPg_fujBD883nv385yKI7hvAA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjv79nMiqXoAhXXFzQIHeFUDXYQ6AEwAnoECAsQAQ#v=onepage&q=diane%20schenandoah&f=false|title=Spawning the Medicine River, Issue 9|last=|publisher=Institute of American Indian Arts Press|date=|via=Google Books|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Art career ==\nSchenandoah became known for her ability to shape clay and carve stone, which she used to create sculptures that would help represent her culture. She additionally worked with wood and antler and casted in 18k gold, sterling silver, and bronze. A few years into her art career, she was taken on as a mentee by sculptor [[Allan Houser]], a famous American sculptor and painter. He even credited her artistry, stating, \u201cI have never had a woman apprentice but if I were to have one, you would be it.\u201d<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.amerinda.org/naar/schenandoahd/carver/carver.htm|title=NAAR {{!}} NATIVE AMERICAN ARTIST ROSTER|website=www.amerinda.org|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref> Schenandoah later stated that these words gave her the confidence and motivation to continue sculpting.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.artslant.com/la/artists/show/330692-diane-schenandoah|title=Diane Schenandoah|website=ArtSlant|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n\nShe has stated that she prefers to use as many natural materials as possible in her sculptures since she believes it was a blessing given to the humans by the hand of the Creator. Schenandoah has stated that she takes inspiration from multiple sources, such as using her own motherhood to inspire a series of sculptures featuring mothers holding their babies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amerinda.org/newsletter/5-3/giveitback.jpg|title=Diane Schenandoah|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to her sculptures, Schenandoah has a line of jewelry in honor of women being life givers.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/diane-schenandoah-b514285/|title=Schenandoah's Originals|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nSchenandoah has received multiple awards, which includes the [https://www.firstpeoplesfund.org/community-spirit-awards Community Spirit Award] from the [https://www.firstpeoplesfund.org/ First People\u2019s Fund]. She received this for her devotion to serving her community at Oneida, where she teaches creative writing, sculpting, and culture presentations. Schenandoah teaches in both public and private schools and offers private art lessons in clay and sculpture.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Select artworks ==\n\n* \u201cCalling All of Creation\u201d - Created using Ohio clay mounted on a black walnut base. The \"turtle rattles\" in the artwork were made from buffalo horn and the gustoays (hat) feathers that the two [[Iroquois|Haudenosaunee]] men are wearing were carved from wampum cohog shells and wild turkey feathers. This sculpture displays two Haudenosaunee men sitting down and facing each other on a bench as they shake their turtle rattles to a sacred form song.<ref name=\":1\" />\n* \u201cShhh\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpeoplesfund.org/diane-schenandoah|title=Diane Schenandoah|website=First Peoples Fund|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> - Created using clay. This sculpture depicts a mother intimately rocking and comforting her baby to sleep.<ref name=\":1\" />\n* \u201cBreath of Life\u201d<ref name=\":1\" /> - Created from original deer bone. This miniature piece can either be worn as a stickpin or part of a necklace. This sculpture honors women as life givers, which was a common theme for many of Schenandoah's artworks.<ref name=\":1\" />\n*\"The Journey Home\" (2005) - Created using buffalo leg bone, caribou antler, and butternut wood. This sculpture was formed to honor her ancestors and the path they journeyed, leading them back to the spirit world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/29261037@N02/21016993291|title=The Journey Home|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*\"Dancing with the Light\" (2014) - Created using maple, white ash, mixed clay, and geese feathers. 14\" x 3\" x 13\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paddle8.com/work/diane-schenandoah/60215-dancing-with-the-light/|title=Diane Schenandoah - Dancing with the Light, 2014|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*\u201cBeholding Beauty\u201d<ref name=\":2\" /> (2010) - Created using clay. 18\" x 24\".<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Select exhibitions ==\n\n*[[Heard Museum|Heard Museum Opening, Phoenix, AZ]]\n\n*[[Pow wow|Pow wow, Cruise, Bahamas]]\n*[[Everson Museum of Art|Traveling Exhibition, Everson Museum of Art, Barnes and Noble, Syracuse, NY]]\n*[[Munson-Williams-Proctor Arts Institute|Munson Williams Proctor School of Art, Utica, NY Schweinfurth Memorial Art Center, Auburn, NY]]\n*[[Six Nations|Six Nations - Six Artists, San Francisco, CA]]\n*[[Castellani Art Museum|Shadow of the Eagle, Castellani Art Museum, Niagara, NY]]\n*[[New York State Museum]] - Iroquois Artists, Albany, NY\n*[[Landmark Theatres|Silent Art Auction, Landmark Theater, Syracuse, NY]]\n*[[Sainte Marie among the Iroquois|Iroquois Artists of Today, St. Marie Among the Iroquois Museum, Liverpool, NY]]\n*[[Iroquois Indian Museum|Iroquois Museum Schoharie, NY]]\n*[[United World Colleges|United World College, Encounter New Mexico Juried Exhibit, Las Vegas, NM]]\n*[[Syracuse University|Bird Library, Syracuse University, Iroquois Art, Syracuse, NY]]\n*[[Berkshire Museum|Berkshire Museum, Women spirit; Focus on Women Regional, Pittsfield, MA]]\n*[[Navy Pier|Chicago's Navy Pier, Native Arts Conference]]\n*[[New York State Museum|New York State Museum, Thanksgiving Show, Iroquois Artist Today, 1983, Albany, NY]]\n*[[Institute of American Indian Arts|I.A.I.A., Graduates Show 1982]]\n\n* [[Fenimore Art Museum|Fennimore Museum, gift shop, Cooperstown, NY]]\n\n*[[Iroquois Indian Museum|Iroquois Indian Museum, Howe's Cave, NY]]\n\n* [[Seneca Niagara Casino & Hotel|The Seneca/Niagara Casino, Niagara Falls, NY]]\n* [[Mashantucket Pequot Museum and Research Center|Mashantucket/Pequot Museum, Ledyard, CT]]\n\n== Collections ==\n\n* Rancocus Nation Museum, Rancocus, NJ\n\n* New York State Museum, Albany, NY\n\n* \u201cThaw Collection\u201d Fennimore Museum, Cooperstown, NY\n\n* Mashentucket/Pequot Museum, Ledyard Ct\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n<br />\n[[Category:Oneida people]]\n[[Category:Native American artists]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Native American sculptors]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography:Typo fixing, replaced: to  to  \u2192  to", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diane_Schenandoah"}
